q("mid1102","mid1",L8,"A patient develops swelling, low blood pressure, and wheezing after taking an antibiotic. What is the most appropriate initial treatment?",["Norepinephrine","Epinephrine (adrenaline) IM","Diphenhydramine only","Corticosteroids only"],1,"Clinical picture (urticaria, hypotension, bronchospasm) after antibiotic = anaphylaxis (Type B ADR). Mediator: histamine. Treatment of anaphylaxis: EPINEPHRINE (adrenaline) IM is the drug of choice."),
q("mid1103","mid1",L8,"Eye drops for acute glaucoma (pilocarpine) taken in overdose IV — which adverse effect occurs?",["Xerostomia (dry mouth)","Excessive salivation (cholinergic toxidrome)","Tachycardia","Mydriasis (pupil dilation)"],1,"Pilocarpine is a muscarinic agonist. Systemic overdose causes cholinergic toxidrome: excessive salivation, lacrimation, sweating, vomiting, diarrhea (SLUDGE), bradycardia, miosis."),
q("mid1104","mid1",L8,"Mechanism of action of Sulfamethoxazole + Trimethoprim (Co-trimoxazole):",["Inhibiting folate synthesis and reduction (two sequential steps in nucleic acid synthesis)","Inhibiting RNA polymerase","Inhibiting cell wall synthesis","Inhibiting 50S ribosomal subunit"],0,"Co-trimoxazole works by double sequential blockade: Sulfamethoxazole inhibits dihydropteroate synthase (step 1); Trimethoprim inhibits dihydrofolate reductase (step 2). Together: synergistic inhibition of bacterial nucleic acid synthesis."),
q("mid1105","mid1",L9,"For a patient with dehydration AND caloric requirement (NPO patient), the most appropriate IV fluid is:",["5% Dextrose in Water (D5W)","Normal saline (0.9% NaCl)","Ringer's lactate","3% NaCl (hypertonic saline)"],0,"D5W (5% Dextrose in Water) provides 170 cal/L (caloric support for NPO patients). Isotonic in bag, becomes hypotonic after dextrose metabolized. Used for dehydration, NPO maintenance."),
q("mid1106","mid1",L9,"Large volumes of NORMAL SALINE (0.9% NaCl) may cause:",["Hyponatremia","Hyperchloremic metabolic acidosis","Hypokalemia","Hypocalcemia"],1,"Normal saline contains 154 mEq/L of Cl⁻ — MORE chloride than plasma (104 mEq/L). Large volumes → hyperchloremic metabolic acidosis (excess chloride drives bicarbonate down)."),
q("mid1107","mid1",L9,"HYPOTONIC fluids shift water:",["Into plasma","Into blood vessels","Into cells (intracellular space)","Into RBCs only"],2,"Hypotonic solutions (<280 mOsm/L) have lower osmolality than plasma. Water shifts by osmosis from ECF into the HIGHER osmolality intracellular space → cells swell. Used for hypernatremia, DKA. Avoided in ↑ICP."),
q("mid1108","mid1",L9,"Best fluid for SEVERE SYMPTOMATIC HYPONATREMIA (coma, seizures):",["Ringer's lactate","D5W","3% NaCl (hypertonic saline)","5% Albumin"],2,"Hypertonic saline (3% NaCl): osmolality ≥375 mOsm/L. Draws water OUT of cells → raises serum sodium rapidly. Indication: severe symptomatic hyponatremia (coma, seizures, Na⁺ <120). Must give slowly via central venous line."),
q("mid1109","mid1",L9,"5% ALBUMIN works by:",["Providing caloric support","Correcting serum sodium levels","Diluting co-infused drugs","Increasing colloid oncotic pressure"],3,"5% Albumin is a colloid. Increases colloid oncotic pressure in the intravascular space → draws fluid from interstitial space into bloodstream → expands intravascular volume. Used for volume expansion, severe hypoalbuminemia."),
q("mid1110","mid1",L9,"Normal saline is appropriate in all of the following EXCEPT:",["Hemorrhagic shock resuscitation","Diluting packed red blood cells","Mild hyponatremia correction","Patient with hyperchloremia or metabolic acidosis"],3,"Normal saline is contraindicated (or inappropriate) in patients with hyperchloremia or existing metabolic acidosis because its high chloride content worsens the acidosis. Ringer's lactate is preferred in such cases."),
q("mid1111","mid1",L8,"A patient takes MORPHINE overdose and is given NALOXONE. Respiratory depression is reversed. Naloxone's pharmacological effect is:",["Competitive antagonist at opioid receptors","Non-pharmacological antidote","Partial agonist at opioid receptors","Direct respiratory stimulant"],0,"Naloxone is a pure competitive antagonist at opioid receptors (μ, κ, δ). It displaces morphine from opioid receptors → reverses all opioid effects. High affinity for opioid receptors but NO intrinsic activity."),
q("mid1112","mid1",L5,"Biotransformation of a drug is primarily directed to:",["Inactivate a drug completely","Activate all prodrugs","Convert lipid-soluble drug to non-lipid-soluble metabolite","Convert non-lipid-soluble drug to lipid-soluble metabolite"],2,"The primary goal of drug biotransformation is to convert LIPOPHILIC (lipid-soluble) drugs into MORE HYDROPHILIC (non-lipid-soluble) metabolites that can be renally excreted. Direction is always toward increased water solubility."),
q("mid1113","mid1",L3,"Which property facilitates a drug's ability to cross the blood-brain barrier?",["Lipophilic (lipid-soluble)","Hydrophilic","High molecular weight","High plasma protein binding"],0,"The BBB only allows lipophilic, unionized, small MW, low protein-bound drugs to cross by passive diffusion. Hydrophilic and ionized drugs are excluded. High protein binding limits BBB crossing."),
q("mid1114","mid1",L7,"RIFAMPIN taken with ORAL CONTRACEPTIVES leads to:",["Increased estrogen levels","Contraceptive failure","No significant interaction","Estrogen toxicity"],1,"Rifampin induces CYP3A4 → faster metabolism of estrogens/progestins → reduced plasma levels → contraceptive failure. This is Type F ADR (Failure of Efficacy). Patients must use additional contraception."),
