q("mid218","mid2",C2,"A 48-year-old presents with dilated pupils, dry mucous membranes, tachycardia, urinary retention, absent bowel sounds, hallucinations. Diagnosis?",["Organophosphate poisoning","Opioid overdose","Atropine toxicity (anticholinergic syndrome)","Beta-blocker overdose"],2,"Classic 'anticholinergic toxidrome': Blind as a bat (mydriasis), Dry as a bone (anhidrosis), Hot as a hare (hyperthermia), Red as a beet, Mad as a hatter (hallucinations/delirium), tachycardia, urinary retention."),
q("mid219","mid2",C2,"A woman prescribed an anticholinergic for motion sickness later experiences vivid dreams and hallucinations. Which drug was most likely used?",["Atropine","Glycopyrrolate","Scopolamine","Dicyclomine"],2,"Scopolamine (hyoscine) has greater CNS penetration than atropine → used for motion sickness but can cause CNS excitation, vivid dreams, hallucinations, especially in females pre-anesthetically."),
q("mid220","mid2",C2,"A patient planning a sea trip has a history of severe nausea during travel. Which drug is most likely prescribed?",["Scopolamine","Salbutamol","Propranolol","Fluoxetine"],0,"Scopolamine (hyoscine) is the preferred antiemetic for motion sickness — more effective than atropine for this indication (blocks vestibular M1 receptors). Available as transdermal patch."),
q("mid221","mid2",C2,"A child with acute iridocyclitis is prescribed a mydriatic-cycloplegic. Which drug is preferred due to SHORTER duration of action?",["Atropine (7 days)","Tropicamide (6 hours)","Scopolamine (3 days)","Glycopyrrolate"],1,"Tropicamide produces mydriasis/cycloplegia for ~6 hours; cyclopentolate ~24 hours; atropine lasts up to 7 days. Shorter-acting preferred for easier reversal."),
q("mid222","mid2",C2,"Which of the following is NOT an indication for antimuscarinic drugs?",["Motion sickness","Parkinson's disease","Bladder spasms","Narrow angle glaucoma"],3,"Narrow angle glaucoma is a CONTRAINDICATION — antimuscarinics cause mydriasis → ↑IOP → worsening of narrow-angle glaucoma. Antimuscarinics ARE indicated for: motion sickness, Parkinson's, bladder spasms, bradycardia, preanesthesia."),
q("mid223","mid2",C2,"Which of the following is NOT a therapeutic indication of antimuscarinic drugs?",["Atrial fibrillation","Postoperative bladder spasm","Motion sickness","Parkinson's disease"],0,"AF is NOT an indication for antimuscarinics. Atropine IS used for BRADYCARDIA (not AF). Antimuscarinics are indicated for: motion sickness, bladder spasms, Parkinson's, preanesthesia, GI colic."),
