q("mid225","mid2",C2,"At a steady-state dose of 0.5 mg atropine, what effect is expected?",["Coma","Dry mouth and skin","Bradykinesia","Hallucinations/delirium"],1,"Atropine dose-dependent effects: 0.5 mg → mild dryness, possible slight initial bradycardia; 1 mg → dry mouth + ↑HR; 2 mg → mydriasis, blurred vision; 5+ mg → hallucinations, delirium, coma."),
q("mid226","mid2",C2,"Which adverse effect is expected after administration of an anticholinergic (atropine)?",["Urinary incontinence","Cycloplegia (paralysis of accommodation)","Diarrhea","Excessive salivation"],1,"Atropine blocks M3 in ciliary muscle → paralysis of accommodation (cycloplegia) and mydriasis. It causes urinary RETENTION (not incontinence), CONSTIPATION, and DRY mouth."),
q("mid227","mid2",C2,"A patient with BPH is about to undergo prostatectomy. Which drug is absolutely contraindicated?",["Scopolamine","Propranolol","Labetalol","Metoprolol"],0,"Scopolamine (antimuscarinic) → urinary retention → absolutely contraindicated in BPH patients. Any antimuscarinic would be contraindicated; scopolamine is the only antimuscarinic listed here."),
q("mid228","mid2",C2,"Why is ipratropium bromide preferred over scopolamine in treating chronic pulmonary obstruction?",["Better oral bioavailability","Fewer CNS side effects (quaternary amine)","No effects on bronchial secretions","More potent bronchodilation than scopolamine"],1,"Ipratropium is a quaternary amine → does NOT cross BBB → fewer CNS side effects. Inhaled route also limits systemic effects. Used in asthma and COPD management."),
q("mid229","mid2",C2,"A COPD patient on inhaled ipratropium develops tolerance after prolonged use. What is the mechanism?",["Receptor downregulation of M3","Tachyphylaxis at the bronchial level","Blockade of presynaptic M2 autoreceptors increases ACh release which overcomes M3 blockade","Drug metabolism increases over time"],2,"Ipratropium is non-selective (blocks M2 and M3). Blockade of presynaptic M2 autoreceptors → ↑ACh release → overcomes M3 blockade → tolerance. Tiotropium (selective M3) does NOT block M2 → no tolerance."),
q("mid230","mid2",C2,"A COPD patient prescribed an inhaled anticholinergic does NOT develop tolerance after prolonged use. Which drug?",["Tiotropium","Ipratropium","Succinylcholine","Benztropine"],0,"Tiotropium is SELECTIVE M3 blocker → does not block presynaptic M2 → no ↑ACh → no tolerance. Also longer acting (once daily) for COPD maintenance. Preferred over ipratropium for chronic COPD."),
q("mid231","mid2",C2,"A 60-year-old with urinary urgency/incontinence is prescribed a selective M3 antagonist. Which is most appropriate?",["Ipratropium","Scopolamine","Solifenacin","Pancuronium"],2,"Solifenacin, darifenacin, and oxybutynin are uroselective M3 blockers → relax bladder detrusor wall → used for urge incontinence and overactive bladder."),
q("mid232","mid2",C2,"A 70-year-old with Parkinson's experiencing excessive salivation and tremors. Which drug is most appropriate?",["Glycopyrrolate","Benztropine","Ipratropium","Oxybutynin"],1,"Benztropine (and biperiden, benzhexol/trihexyphenidyl) are antiparkinsonian antimuscarinics that cross BBB → reduce tremors and sialorrhea in Parkinson's disease and drug-induced parkinsonism."),
q("mid233","mid2",C2,"A colonoscopy patient receives an IM anticholinergic to relax the intestine. What other adverse effect could occur?",["Urinary incontinence","Cycloplegia (blurred vision)","Diarrhea","Excessive salivation"],1,"Antimuscarinics → block M3 in ciliary muscle → cycloplegia (blurred vision, loss of accommodation). Also cause dry mouth, urinary RETENTION, tachycardia — NOT incontinence or diarrhea."),
q("mid234","mid2",C2,"Which of the following drugs antagonizes the action of tubocurarine (non-depolarizing NMB)?",["Halothane","Neostigmine","Gentamicin","Diltiazem"],1,"Tubocurarine is a non-depolarizing (competitive) NMB. Neostigmine (AChE inhibitor) ↑ACh in synaptic cleft → competes with tubocurarine at NMJ → reverses blockade. Aminoglycosides and halothane POTENTIATE the block."),
q("mid235","mid2",C2,"A patient given a neuromuscular blocker has initial muscle fasciculations followed by paralysis. Which drug?",["Pancuronium","Succinylcholine","Rocuronium","Vecuronium"],1,"Succinylcholine is the ONLY depolarizing NMB — acts as ACh agonist → initial fasciculations (depolarization phase) → sustained depolarization → paralysis (Phase II block). Non-depolarizing agents cause NO fasciculations."),
q("mid236","mid2",C2,"After surgery, the anesthesiologist gives neostigmine to reverse neuromuscular blockade. Which drug was used initially?",["Succinylcholine","Pancuronium","Atropine","Tiotropium"],1,"Only non-depolarizing NMBs (pancuronium, rocuronium, vecuronium) are reversible with neostigmine. Succinylcholine is a DEPOLARIZING NMB — NOT reversed by AChE inhibitors (giving neostigmine worsens the block)."),
